## What this project is

**dumpexe** is a Linux-side RE toolkit for **16-bit real-mode MS-DOS** binaries (roughly 1980–1990). It is part of **RetroCodeMess** (author: EdgeOfAssembly), dual-licensed GPLv2 / commercial.

**Stated long-term goal** (from your message, beyond current README):  
preserve classic DOS games that can no longer be bought → produce **UASM-assemblable** disassembly that runs under **DOSBox**, and eventually **C23 ports** for Linux.

**What exists today** is the analyzer half of that pipeline: inspect → dump → disassemble → lightly simulate. It does **not** yet emit UASM listings, rebuild scripts, or C ports.

---

## Architecture (header-only + one translation unit)

| Layer | Files | Role |
|--------|--------|------|
| Entry | `dumpexe.cpp` | CLI, load file, format detect, dispatch |
| Umbrella | `dumpexe.h` | Includes everything |
| Formats | `exe.h`, `com.h`, `sys.h` | Packed structs / constants |
| Analysis | `analysis.h`, `com_analysis.h`, `sys_analysis.h` | Headers, reloc, hex, simulate |
| Disasm | `disasm.h` | Capstone x86-16, INT comments |
| INT DB | `gen_int_db.py` + `interrupts/INTERRUP.*` → `int_db.h` | RBIL → compile-time table |
| INT lookup | `int_annotate.h` | Exact / AH / generic match |
| CPU model | `registers.h` | Global AX…FLAGS (unions + bitfields) |
| CLI / UI | `options.h`, `formatting.h` | Flags, TDUMP-style output |
| Docs | `README.md`, `dumpexe.1`, `examples/` | Usage + sample dumps |

Build: **C++23**, **GCC**, **static**, **Capstone mandatory**. `make` regenerates `int_db.h` from Ralph Brown’s Interrupt List (release 61 in-tree).

```
file bytes
    │
    ├─ MZ (5A4D) ────────► validate → header → reloc → hex → disasm → simulate
    ├─ FFFFFFFFh ────────► .SYS driver header → hex/disasm strategy+interrupt
    └─ else ─────────────► .COM (+ PSP heuristic / --psp / --no-psp)
```

---

## Capabilities today

1. **Format detection** by content (not extension).
2. **MZ EXE**: full header, sizes, CS:IP / SS:SP, reloc table + padding, entry→EOF hexdump, Capstone disasm, DOS load sim (base segment default `1000h`).
3. **.COM**: PSP auto-detect (`CD 20` + command-tail CR), load model printout, same hex/disasm/sim path.
4. **.SYS**: 18-byte driver header, attr decode, known block signatures, strategy/interrupt dump/disasm.
5. **INT annotations** on `int imm` using last seen `mov ah/al/ax, imm` (static path) or live AH/AL (sim path).
6. **“Simulator”** is intentionally light: set DOS startup registers, show reloc fixups, trace **~20** instructions with mov/xor/sub/add/push/pop/call/ret/int only. Not a full emulator (no memory writes, no INT handlers, no branching model).

Default (no `-r/-x/-d`): header + **64-byte** entry-point hex preview.

