## Simulator: what it does **today**

**No — it does not model a real PC’s 1 MB real-mode map.**

What exists is a **best-effort startup trace**, not an emulator:

| Piece | Reality in dumpexe |
|--------|---------------------|
| Address space | No flat 00000–FFFFF RAM array |
| IVT / BDA (`0000:0000`, `0040:0000`) | Not present |
| BIOS ROM (`F000:…`) | Not present |
| Video (`A000`/`B000`/`B800`) | Not present |
| Conventional RAM | Not allocated as a block |
| PSP | **256-byte synthetic** blob; only a few fields (e.g. `[0002]` mem top = `A000h`) |
| Program image | Read-through from the **file** when CS/DS hits the load image |
| Execution | ~40 instructions; `mov`/`add`/`cmp`/`shl`/`call`/`jmp`/`jcc`/stack; **no** full memory write model, **no** INT handlers |

So when the sim prints `DS=0FF0h` (PSP) and `CS=1000h` (image), those are **register labels**, not “byte at linear `0FF00` in a 1 MB arena.” `rep movsb` is not actually copying PSP into a data segment in RAM.

Authentic DOS layout would look more like:

```
0000:0000  IVT
0040:0000  BDA
…          DOS + drivers
XXXX:0000  PSP (256 bytes)
XXXX+10:0  MZ load image   ← --base today ≈ this
A000:0000  VGA/EGA
B800:0000  CGA text
F000:0000  BIOS
```

ICON’s Pascal check `cmp ax, [ds:0002]` only “works” because we **fake** PSP word 2 as `A000h`, not because we simulated 640K of free RAM.

